Preheat your oven to 220°C. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(peeled and sliced into half moons). Halve, then remove the core from the @green pepper{1}(halved and cored) and thinly slice. Cut the @chorizo stick{1}(cut in half lengthways, skin removed) and slice into ½cm wide half moons. Drain and rinse the @black beans{1%400g can} in a #sieve{}. Finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(finely chopped) (stalks and all). Grate the @lime{1}(zested).

Heat a glug of oil in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Add the chorizo, cook for ~{5%minutes}. Remove from the pan, set aside. Add the onion and pepper to the pan. Cook until soft, ~{5%minutes}. Stir in the @tomato puree{30%g} and @Mexican spice{3/4%tsp}, cook for ~{1%minute} more. Add the black beans, chorizo, @water{125%ml} and pop on a #lid{}. Reduce the heat to medium, cook for ~{5%minutes}.

Once the 5 mins are up, remove the lid from your pan. Simmer until the liquid has almost evaporated, ~{3-4%minutes}, then remove from the heat. Roughly mash the mixture with a #potato masher{}. Stir in the parsley and lime zest. Taste and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} if needed. Lay the @super soft tortillas with whole wheat{4} on a #board{} (two per person), spoon the mixture down the centre of each, then roll them up into cylinders.

Drizzle a little oil over the bottom of an #ovenproof dish{}, then lay in the tortillas. Pack them snugly side by side, with the folded edge downwards so they don't unroll. Spoon the @creme fraiche{1} over the top and then spread it out evenly. Grate the @mature cheddar cheese{60%g} and sprinkle on top, then bake on the top shelf of your oven until golden brown, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Meanwhile, squeeze the @lime{1}(juiced) juice into a large #bowl{}. Add the @honey{1} and @olive oil{1}. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Whisk together with a #fork{} and your dressing is made! Halve the @cucumber{1/2}(halved lengthways, seeds scraped out) lengthways, scrape out the seeds with a #teaspoon{} (discard the seeds) and chop the flesh into 1cm chunks.

When the enchiladas are cooked, remove from the oven and leave to cool slightly for ~{2%minutes}. Toss the @baby leaves{1} and cucumber in the dressing. Serve the chorizo enchiladas on plates with the salad alongside. Enjoy!

> Mexican food is recognised by UNESCO as an 'Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity'. We're not entirely sure what that means but we're in favour of anything that gives props to things that are delicious. And Mexican food is undeniably delicious. Like this enchilada recipe which is bursting with black beans and chorizo. Buen provecho!